>BLISS-10 is far simpler - perhaps has little more than that peephole
>optimizer.  BLISS-10 compares to its successors like the PDP-11 C
>compiler compares to gcc.

It's worse than that.  The BLISS compilers before DECnet
are different than the BLISS compilers after DECnet.
That BLISS-11 that you guys are talking about is a before-DECnet
compiler. 

Comparing before-DECnet BLISSes with after-DECnet-BLISSes
is more like comparing FORTRAN II with FORTRAN IV.  

And it even gets more complicated than that because BLISS
development continued a CMU _without us getting any of the
updates_.  So BLISS-10 and BLISS-11 compiler development
is really some flavor of compiler that had been frozen
in the early 70s (I'm guessing) or so.

The person we need for all of this BLISS-10 and RMS stuff
is Eric Macgrath.  Somebody go kick him.

/BAH

